  "prompt": "Does Cyanogen 13.1 on Moto G3 support VOLTE? If yes, how can I turn on?",
  "response": "As of Cyanogen OS 13.1 for the Moto G3, **VoLTE (Voice over LTE) support is generally not officially supported**. The Moto G3 (Moto 6) was released in 2016, and while the hardware might have some capability for enhanced voice services, the combination of Cyanogen OS 13.1 and the Moto G3 doesn't natively support VoLTE due to several factors:\n\n1. **Software Limitations**: Cyanogen OS was discontinued and succeeded by LineageOS. Custom ROMs like Cyanogen OS often rely on open-source components and may lack proprietary drivers or firmware necessary for features like VoLTE.\n\n2. **Carrier Support**: VoLTE availability heavily depends on your carrier's network and whether they support VoLTE on the Moto G3. Even if the hardware and software could theoretically support VoLTE, carrier-specific settings and configurations are essential.\n\n3. **Modem Firmware**: VoLTE requires specific modem firmware that can handle LTE voice communications. Custom ROMs may not include the necessary firmware, and flashing proprietary modem images can be risky and may not be available.\n\n### What You Can Try:\n\nIf you still want to attempt enabling VoLTE on your Moto G3 running Cyanogen OS 13.1, you can try the following steps. However, **please proceed with caution**, as modifying system settings can lead to instability or other issues.\n\n1. **Check Carrier Support**:\n   - Ensure your carrier supports VoLTE on the Moto G3.\n   - Insert a SIM card from a carrier known to support VoLTE on this device.\n\n2. **Update APN Settings**:\n   - Go to **Settings** > **More** > **Mobile Networks** > **Access Point Names (APN)**.\n   - Ensure that your APN settings are correctly configured for your carrier. Sometimes, incorrect APN settings can prevent VoLTE from working.\n\n3. **Enable VoLTE in Settings**:\n   - Navigate to **Settings** > **More** > **Mobile Networks**.\n   - Look for an option labeled **VoLTE**, **HD Voice**, or similar.\n   - If available, toggle it **On**.\n\n4. **Use a VoLTE Enabler App or Xposed Module**:\n   - Some users have reported success using apps or modules that can modify hidden settings.\n   - **Note**: This method typically requires root access and knowledge of the Xposed Framework. It can be risky and may void warranties or cause system instability.\n   - Proceed only if you're comfortable with advanced Android modifications.\n\n5. **Flash a Different ROM or Modem**:\n   - Some custom ROMs based on LineageOS might have better support for VoLTE.\n   - Alternatively, if you can find a compatible modem (radio) firmware that supports VoLTE for the Moto G3, flashing it might enable the feature.\n   - **Warning**: Flashing the wrong firmware can brick your device. Always ensure compatibility and follow detailed guides.\n\n### Alternative Solution:\n\nGiven the complexities and potential risks associated with enabling VoLTE on a device and ROM that doesn't officially support it, you might consider:\n\n- **Switching to a ROM that Supports VoLTE**: Look for updated custom ROMs based on LineageOS that might have better support for voice services. Check forums like XDA Developers for user experiences and guides specific to the Moto G3.\n\n- **Using Stock ROM**: If VoLTE is crucial for you, reverting to the stock Motorola ROM might be the most straightforward solution, provided that the stock firmware for your region and carrier supports VoLTE on the Moto G3.\n\n### Final Recommendations:\n\n- **Backup Your Data**: Before making any changes, ensure you have a complete backup of your device.\n- **Consult Community Forums**: Platforms like XDA Developers have active communities where you can find device-specific advice and potentially more up-to-date methods or ROMs that support VoLTE.\n- **Proceed with Caution**: Customizing system-level features can lead to unexpected behavior. Ensure you understand the steps and risks involved.\n\nIf VoLTE is a critical feature for your daily use, evaluating the benefits of upgrading to a more recent device that offers native support might be worth considering.\n\n---\n\n*Please note that my knowledge is based on information available up to October 2023, and newer developments or community solutions may exist beyond this point.*",
